<dl id="n54119c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54119c">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54119c"> 119(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Kung the Tall, <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54119c"><li>FW 52.25 </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/lexc.htm#n54119c">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/c/l39c.htm#n54119c">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54119c">MS BL 47476a-172</ms> </li><li>JJA 49:365 <a name="cd10" href="../../FF/fdra/cda.htm#cd10">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/c/cd10.htm#n54119c">Draft: I.3&sect;1.10</a>/2.10/3.10</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Having reached the ripe old age of seventy <mark>Kung the Tall</mark> who was living in what is now the province of Shantung in Norther China drew up a well considered balance sheet of his earthy accounts, putting on the credit side all the accomplishments in which he took pride and on the debit side all the worthy desires and ambitions which the passing years had left unfulfilled. <small> Carl Crow, <a name="CCMK" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CCMK"><cite title="source">Master Kung. The Story of Confucius</cite></a> (Sep 1937) 21</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Kung the Tall, the father of Confucius, was an exceptionally strong and tall man (7 foot). He spent most of his life soldiering, but in his declining years he was in civil employment in the service of the Duke of Lu. His ancestors&mdash;who included the great Dukes of Chow&mdash;had lived in the neighbouring feudal state of Sung, but the grandfather of Kung the Tall had moved to Lu. </mm> </dd></dl>
